# Zeros Don’t Lie: A Data-Driven Apology

## Overview
A personal analysis of academic performance, procrastination, and self-reflection using data visualization and predictive modeling.

## Repository Structure
```
Zeros-Dont-Lie/
│-- data/
│   ├── personal_grades.csv
│-- scripts/
│   ├── data_analysis.R
│   ├── procrastination_patterns.R
│-- visualizations/
│   ├── grade_trends.png
│   ├── submission_timeline.png
│-- README.md
│-- final_presentation.pdf
```

## Technologies Used
- R (ggplot2, dplyr, tidymodels)
- Logistic Regression
- Data Visualization

## Key Insights
- Late submissions had a significant impact on overall grades.
- Predictive analysis showed how hypothetical effort adjustments could lead to an 84% total grade.
- Visual patterns revealed inconsistencies in academic discipline.

## Getting Started
1. Clone this repository:
   ```bash
   git clone https://github.com/username/Zeros-Dont-Lie.git
   ```
2. Run `data_analysis.R` to preprocess and clean the dataset.
3. Use `procrastination_patterns.R` to analyze submission behaviors.
4. View results in `visualizations/` folder.

---

These repositories serve as both portfolio pieces and technical demonstrations of data-driven storytelling.
